    "image_with_text_fxf8r4": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_EpxyUG": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>What are Heel Spurs? </strong>The calcaneus (heel bone) is the largest bone in the foot and absorbs the most amount of shock and pressure. A heel spur develops as an abnormal growth of the heel bone. Calcium deposits form when the plantar fascia pulls away from the heel area, causing a bony protrusion, or heel spur. The plantar fascia is a broad band of fibrous tissue located along the bottom surface of the foot that runs from the heel to the forefoot. Heel spurs can cause extreme pain in the rearfoot, especially while standing or walking.<br/><br/><strong>Aetrex Heel Spurs Orthotics:</strong><br/>Aetrex Heel Spurs Orthotics are specifically designed with an absent heel pod to help redistribute pressure away from the center of the heel where the spur is located. This redistribution of pressure helps reduce pain and allows for the area to heal. In addition Aetrex’s strategically placed arch support aligns your body to help reduce overpronation and support your body from the ground up.</p><p><strong>Price:</strong> Available Now for $69.95</p>",
            "text_font": "body",
            "text_size": "subtext-md",
            "text_max_size": 32,
            "secondary_color": false,
            "highlighted_text": "none",
            "highlighted_scribble": "circle"
          }
